oai_dc:dc.dc:title: HURRICANE HARVEY COASTAL EFFECTS IN TEXAS
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Kennedy, Andrew
Kijewski-Correa, Tracy
Taflanidis, Alexandros
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Hurricane Harvey made landfall in Texas on August 26, 2017, causing severe wind, wave, and surge damage to homes and businesses. Several weeks after landfall, National Science Foundation-funded teams of researchers performed reconnaissance related to winds and water levels, erosion, and damage caused by the storm. This paper will describe these efforts, the effects of Harvey's winds, waves, and surge, and will present preliminary conclusions.
oai_dc:dc.dc:source: Coastal Engineering Proceedings; No. 36 (2018): Proceedings of 36th Conference on Coastal Engineering, Baltimore, Maryland, 2018; waves.61
